generated_caption: The line chart illustrates the gross heat consumed from geothermal energy in the United Kingdom (UK) over five years, from 2014 to 2018. Bartenders, waiters/waitresses, crew persons, host/hostesses, dishwasher/bus persons, and chefs or cooks also have high agreement rates ranging from 89% to 97%, with corresponding lower disagreement percentages between 4% and 10%.

The histogram illustrates the number of previous jobs held by restaurant operators in the U.S. as of October 2013. The data shows that 85% had been restaurant managers, 61% shift or crew supervisors, 59% chefs or cooks, 55% waiters or waitresses, 49% dishwashers, 42% hosts or hostesses, 38% bartenders, 37% bus persons, and 34% crew persons (fast food).

The bar chart illustrates the number of male and female competitors in various sports events affected by COVID-19 in 2020. The data includes tennis with 2 males and 1 female, basketball with 5 males and 2 females, volleyball with 32 males and 27 females, soccer with 19 males and 16 females, and hockey with 12 males and 16 females. Each event's gender distribution is represented as separate bars for males and females.

The bar chart illustrates the frequency of computer usage in Great Britain in 2017, categorized by age groups. It shows five usage patterns: daily, weekly, less than once a week, used over three months ago, and never used. The 16-24 age group uses computers daily with 79%, while the 25-34 group has 81%. Usage decreases with age, with the 65+ group using computers daily at 51%. Weekly use is highest among the 16-24 and 55-64 age groups at 12% and 11%, respectively. The 'Never used' category increases with age, peaking at 28% for those aged 65+.

The pie chart illustrates the share of video games studios with over four employees in the United Kingdom from 2012 to 2015. In 2012, these studios held a 23% share, which increased to 30% by 2015. The year 2013 saw a 19% share, while 2014 had a slight increase to 28%. Each year shows a different percentage distribution among the video games studios with more than four employees.

The histogram illustrates car dealer satisfaction ratings for various automobile manufacturers in the UK during July 2020. Kia and Lexus lead with scores of 9.5, followed by Toyota at 8.9. Mini, Mercedes-Benz, and Mazda are rated at 8.3, 7.8, and 7.6 respectively. BMW, Suzuki, Nissan, Citroen, and SEAT have scores between 7.1 and 7.4. Mitsubishi, Subaru, and Audi are rated lower at 6.9, 6.7, and 6.2. Volkswagen, Skoda, Dacia, and Ford are scored at 5.4, 5.6, 5.5, and 5.3. General Motors, Alfa Romeo, Jaguar, Abarth, Vauxhall, Fiat, Jeep, and Hyundai have the lowest ratings ranging from 3.5 to 4.5.

The histogram illustrates the number of times various football players have won the FIFA Ballon d'Or award between 1956 and 2020. Lionel Messi leads with six wins, followed by Cristiano Ronaldo with five. Other players who have won multiple times include Georginio Wijnaldum, Marco van Basten, and Johan Cruyff, each with three wins. Ronald Koeman, Franz Beckenbauer, and Zinedine Zidane have two wins apiece, while other players like Lev Yashin, Giorgio Chinaglia, and Romario have one win each.

The bar chart illustrates the distribution of voters at the Academy Awards in 2020 by ethnicity. It shows that 85% of the voters were white, while minority members accounted for 15%. The data suggests a significant disparity in voter representation between these two ethnic groups.

The line chart illustrates insurance benefits and claims in the United Kingdom and Europe from 2004 to 2019. For each year, two values are plotted: one for insurance benefits (in millions) and another for claims (in billions). In 2004, the UK had 150 million in benefits and 630 billion in claims, while Europe had 630 million in benefits and 850 billion in claims. The data shows fluctuations over the years, with the UK's benefits ranging from 150 to 320 million and claims from 630 to 1070 billion, and Europe's benefits varying between 630 and 1050 million and claims between 850 and 1070 billion.

The bar chart illustrates the percentage of adults in Great Britain (UK) who were financially struggling until payday, categorized by region in 2014. The North East had the highest percentage at 57%, followed by London at 49%. The West Midlands and Yorkshire & Humberside regions showed 47% and 46% respectively. The North West had 43%, Wales 42%, and the East region 42% as well. Scotland and the East Midlands both recorded 39%, while the South East and South West regions had the lowest percentages at 38% each.

The bar chart illustrates the forecast for the number of new hotels opening in the Middle East from 2012 to 2016. In 2012, there were 31 new hotels expected to open, which increased to 36 in 2013. The trend continues upward with projections of 52 new hotels in 2014, 56 in 2015, and reaching a peak of 62 new hotels opening in 2016.

The bar chart illustrates the volume of recycled/composted waste collected by local authorities in England from 2000/01 to 2019/20, measured in million metric tons. The data shows an overall increase over the years, starting at 3.5 million metric tons in 2000/01 and reaching 11.2 million metric tons in 2019/20. There is a notable dip in 2004/05 with 7.0 million metric tons, followed by a gradual rise until the peak in 2016/17 at 11.5 million metric tons.

The bar chart illustrates the amount of waste collected by local authorities for landfills in North East England from 2000 to 2018, measured in thousands of metric tons. The data spans two-year intervals, starting with 1100 thousand metric tons in 2000/01 and ending with 105 thousand metric tons in 2017/18. There is a general downward trend in waste collection over the years, with the highest amount being in 2002/03 at 1270 thousand metric tons and the lowest in 2017/18 at 105 thousand metric tons.

The bar chart illustrates the influence of COVID-19 on bill growth in e-groceries across different store formats in Russia during 2020, with data segmented by the Moscow region and total figures. Hypermarkets saw an increase of 22% in the Moscow region and 14% overall. Supermarkets experienced a 21% rise in the Moscow region and 15% in total. Convenience stores had a 24% growth in the Moscow region and 10% for the total.

The histogram illustrates the top 10 strongest nation brand performers in the investment segment for 2014, based on the Brand Strength Index. Singapore leads with a score of 79, followed by Switzerland at 78 and Sweden at 76. Germany is ranked fourth with a score of 75, while Norway comes in fifth with 74. The United States, United Kingdom, Denmark, Finland, and the Netherlands follow, each with scores ranging from 73 to 72.

The bar chart illustrates the recycling rate of waste collected by local authorities in England from 2000/01 to 2019/20. The data shows an upward trend over the years, starting at 12.5% in 2000/01 and reaching 43.8% in 2019/20. Each year marks a consistent increase in the recycling rate, with notable jumps such as from 27.6% in 2005/06 to 30.9% in 2006/07, and a steady climb through subsequent years.

The bar chart illustrates the volumes of household waste that were recycled, composted, or reused in England from 2000 to 2013, measured in kilograms per person. The data spans multiple years, with the lowest volume recorded at 60 kg/person in 2000/01 and the highest at 185 kg/person in 2010/11. There is a general upward trend in waste volumes over the period, peaking in 2010/11 before slightly decreasing in subsequent years.

The line chart illustrates the monthly change in average daily sun hours in the United Kingdom from 2015 to 2020. Each month is represented with its respective change in sun hours, measured in hours, over the six-year period. For example, January shows a decrease of 1 hour in 2015 and an increase of 0.5 hours in 2020. February's changes range from -0.8 to +1.7 hours, while March fluctuates between -0.6 and +1.1 hours. The data for April through December also display varying changes, with some months showing significant fluctuations such as July's change from -0.4 to +2.3 hours.

The bar chart illustrates the deviation of heating degree days from their mean in the United Kingdom from 2010 to 2021. Each month shows how the actual heating degree days compare to the average, with positive values indicating higher than average temperatures and negative values showing lower temperatures. For example, January 2010 had 3.1 deviations above the mean, while April 2019 had -3.5 deviations below the mean. The data spans through various months and years, capturing fluctuations in temperature that could affect heating needs.

The line chart illustrates the growth of PC online games revenue in the Philippines from 2012 to 2014, measured in million U.S. dollars. In 2012, the revenue was $43 million, which increased to $50 million in 2013 and further to $64 million in 2014. Each year shows a consistent rise in revenue, indicating a positive trend over the three-year period.

The line chart illustrates the growth in the number of PC online gamers in Vietnam from 2012 to 2014. In 2012, there were 15.6 million PC online gamers, which increased to 16.2 million in 2013 and further to 19.0 million in 2014. The data points show a consistent upward trend in the number of gamers over these three years.

The bar chart illustrates the total sales volume of best-selling video games for consoles in Japan during 2020, measured in million units. "Animal Crossing: New Horizons" leads with 6.4 million units sold, followed by "Final Fantasy VII Remake (Switch)" at 1.58 million and "Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice (PS4)" at 1.27 million. Other notable titles include "Fallout 76" with 0.93 million units, "Final Fantasy XV" at 0.9 million, "Pokémon Sword/Shield" at 0.84 million, "Super Smash Bros. Ultimate" at 0.57 million, "Minecraft (Switch)" at 0.52 million, "Sonic Worldwide Games (Switch)" at 0.51 million, and "Super Mario 3D All-Stars (Switch)" at 0.48 million units.

The histogram illustrates the leading domestic fall destinations for U.S. travelers as of August 2016. Maui, HI tops the list with a value of 34, followed by Orlando, FL at 32, and New York City, NY at 30. Las Vegas, NV is next with a value of 28, while Cruise - Alaska comes in at 25. Los Angeles, CA has a value of 20, Honolulu, HI at 19, San Francisco, CA at 17, Chicago, IL at 14, and Washington, DC rounds out the list with a value of 12.

The histogram illustrates the popularity of European river cruise destinations among U.S. travelers in August 2014. France leads with a value of 31, followed by Germany at 28, Hungary at 13, The Netherlands at 8, and Austria at 6. Each destination is represented as a separate bar, indicating their respective popularity scores.

The bar chart illustrates public opinion on the priority of completing domestic leagues/competitions versus international fixtures/tournaments in 2020, categorized by age groups. The 18-24 age group is evenly split between those who prioritize domestic events and those who prefer international ones. The 25-34 age group leans towards domestic events with 28% compared to 17% for international fixtures. Those aged 35-44 show a preference for domestic leagues with 35%, while the 45-54 age bracket has a higher percentage for international tournaments at 37%. The 55+ age group is equally divided, with 35% supporting each option. Lastly, 24% of all age groups are undecided.

The line chart illustrates the quarterly average rainfall in the United Kingdom from 2010 to 2021. It shows four distinct seasons: Q1, Q2, Q3, and Q4, with corresponding rainfall values for each year. In 2010, the rainfall was 200 mm in Q1, 150 mm in Q2, 380 mm in Q3, and 300 mm in Q4. The data continues through 2021, with fluctuations in rainfall amounts across the quarters, such as 620 mm in Q1 and 750 mm in Q4 for 2011, and 420 mm in Q1 and 230 mm in Q4 for 2021.

The line chart illustrates the transmission distribution and other losses of the public electricity distribution system in the UK from 2000 to 2020, measured in terawatt hours (TWh). The data shows fluctuations over the years, with losses ranging from a low of 25.4 TWh in 2018 to a high of 33.2 TWh in 2004. Other years display varying levels of loss, such as 32.1 TWh in 2001 and 27.6 TWh in 2020. The chart captures the trend of these losses over two decades.

The line chart illustrates publicly distributed electricity sales in the United Kingdom from 2002 to 2020, measured in terawatt hours (TWh). The data shows fluctuations over the years, starting at 320 TWh in 2002 and peaking at 332 TWh in 2008. Sales dipped slightly in subsequent years but generally remained above 300 TWh until 2014, when they dropped to 290 TWh. A further decline is observed with sales reaching their lowest point of 265 TWh by 2020.

The histogram illustrates the general attractiveness factors of countries worldwide in 2014, measured by the number of respondents who found each factor appealing. Culture is the most attractive factor with 31 responses, followed by Economy and Natural environment both at 15 responses each. Society and Education and science are also considered attractive with 15 and 10 responses respectively. People and Cities are less attractive, receiving 8 and 7 responses from respondents.

The histogram illustrates various factors contributing to the attractiveness of the United Kingdom for tourists in 2014. Cultural and historic attractions lead with a value of 43, followed by cities at 39, countryside and landscapes at 36, and history at 33. Language appeal is rated at 30, while people-friendly policies score 26. The UK's economy, technological advancement, and climate are valued at 22, 21, and 20 respectively. Education, healthcare, and social relations are considered important with values of 17, 17, and 17. By comparison, sports facilities, environmental balance, and levels of government are less attractive, scoring 16, 15, and 10 respectively.

The bar chart illustrates the percentage of smartphone users in the U.S. who pay for mobile news content, segmented by age group in 2014. The average across all age groups is 98%. For those aged 18-34, the percentage drops to 90%, while those aged 35-54 show an increase to 100%. The 55+ age group also has a 90% payment rate for mobile news content.

The bar chart illustrates the frequency of quick service restaurant visits in the UK for 2014, categorized by online video viewership and non-viewership. Online video viewers report visiting restaurants three times a week or more at a rate of 12%, once a week at 12%, once a month at 23%, and never ever at 53%. Non-online video viewers have visit frequencies of 9% for three times a week or more, 8% for once a week, 14% for once a month, and 65% who never visit.

The histogram illustrates the frequency of various tourist "clichés" in the U.S. as of July 2014. It shows that 64% of tourists asked a local for directions, 54% stopped at a franchise, 49% walked down a street with a photo of it, 48% took a photo of a sightseeing tour, 41% took pictures of the city, 38% bought a souvenir, 18% tried to haggle, 17% were planning their next trip, and 15% tried to buy a guide with the top attraction.

The pie chart illustrates the distribution of soft drink purchases by private label/brand in Great Britain for 2012. Premium named brands hold a 12% share, and those who chose not to specify their preference account for 2% of the purchases.

The bar chart illustrates the travel habits of U.S. travelers in 2014, focusing on international travel for holidays within the past year. The data reflects the number of people who have or have not traveled internationally for holidays in the specified time frame.

The bar chart illustrates changes in monthly in-home data usage across various devices in the U.S. for January, February, and March 2020 compared to their respective months in 2019. The line chart illustrates the trend in video game retail revenues from 2012 to 2020, distinguishing between ownership and access models. Ownership revenue starts at $1450 million in 2012 and fluctuates over the years, reaching its peak of $2400 million in 2020. Access revenue begins at $600 million in 2012, showing a consistent upward trend, culminating at $2100 million by 2020. The data points for each year show the progression of both revenue streams within the video game retail sector.

The bar chart illustrates the ranking of leading general food brands by trustworthiness for babies and children in the United Kingdom (UK) in 2013. The histogram illustrates the expectations for permanent headcount among logistics sector staff in the United Kingdom (UK) in 2014. It shows three categories: 'Remain the same' with an expectation of 29%, 'Increase' with 53%, and 'Decrease' with 18%.

The bar chart illustrates the percentage change in food prices across selected EU countries compared to the UK in 2016. The histogram illustrates the leading retail parks in the United Kingdom (UK) for highest rent in 2019, measured in British pounds per square foot. The bar chart illustrates library membership penetration in the U.S. for 2015, categorized by parental status. It shows two groups: those with children in their household and those without. The pie chart illustrates the personal care private label volume share in the United Kingdom for two consecutive months, June 2013 and June 2014. In June 2013, the private label volume share was 51%, whereas it decreased to 49% in June 2014.

The histogram illustrates the emotions of travelers upon arrival at their vacation destinations in July 2014. The data shows various emotional states such as excited (55), energized (34), liberated (24), relaxed (24), open-minded (23), fulfilled (19), confident (17), in control (15), secure (15), passionate (13), challenged (13), knowledgeable (12), closer to loved ones (11), affluent (6), and productive (6). The line chart illustrates the number of active U.S. geocachers from January 2018 to December 2019. In January 2018, there were 475,000 active geocachers, which decreased to 460,000 by July. The bar chart illustrates the health worries among different generations in the U.S. in 2013, with percentages for each generation regarding five health concerns: Alzheimer's, cancer, heart attack, stroke, and diabetes. The Silent Generation is most concerned about Alzheimer's (39%) and cancer (17%), and least worried about diabetes (10%).

The bar chart illustrates the global online shopping order value in Q2 2020 and Q2 2021, segmented by traffic source. Atlántico has 39, Magdalena 35, Nariño 25, Córdoba 21, Meta 17, Tolima 16, Bolívar 14, Cesar 12, and La Guajira 13 cases of femicide.

The line chart illustrates the number of cases of Lyme disease diagnosed in Poland from 2018 to 2020. In 2018, there were 20,500 cases reported. The count increased each year, reaching 21,300 in 2019 and peaking at 22,700 in 2020. However, there was a significant drop in 2021, with only 12,400 cases recorded.

The line chart illustrates the number of measles cases diagnosed in Poland from 2018 to 2020. In 2018, there were 357 cases reported. The count increased each year, reaching 689 cases in 2019 and peaking at 1500 cases in 2020. However, the trend reversed in 2021 with a significant drop to 40 cases.

The line chart illustrates the quarterly youth unemployment rates in Nigeria, comparing two methodologies: NEW Nigeria and International. Data spans from Q1 2018 to Q4 2020. In Q1 2018, the NEW Nigeria methodology shows a rate of 38%, while the International method records 16%. By Q4 2020, the NEW Nigeria rate rises to 53%, whereas the International method increases to 38%. The chart captures fluctuations over these years, with the NEW Nigeria methodology generally showing higher unemployment percentages than the International method.

The line chart illustrates the tourism expenditure on cultural, sports, and leisure services in France from 2010 to 2017. It shows five categories: museums, shows, and other cultural activities; casinos; amusement parks and other recreational services; ski lifts; and cultural, sporting, and recreational services. The data points indicate annual spending in billions of euros for each category over the years. For instance, in 2010, museums, shows, and cultural activities had an expenditure of 2.1 billion euros, while casinos were at 2.3 billion euros. By 2017, these figures increased across all categories, with museums reaching 2.5 billion euros and casinos 2.8 billion euros.

The histogram illustrates the perception of telecommuting during the quarantine in Spain in April 2020, categorized by satisfaction levels. The data shows that 1 person rated their experience as 'very bad', 2 as 'bad', and 3 as 'okay'. A larger group of 8 individuals found it 'good', while 7 rated it 'very good'. The highest satisfaction level is represented by 12 people who deemed their telecommuting experience 'excellent'.

The bar chart illustrates satisfaction levels with distance learning in Russia for 2020, categorized by education level. Parents of graduating schoolchildren show 12% totally satisfied, 32% rather satisfied, 34% rather unsatisfied, 21% totally unsatisfied, and 1% difficult to answer. College/technical college students indicate higher satisfaction with 34% totally satisfied, 40% rather satisfied, 15% rather unsatisfied, 9% totally unsatisfied, and 2% difficult to answer. Higher education students report 25% totally satisfied, 50% rather satisfied, 21% rather unsatisfied, 5% totally unsatisfied, and 3% difficult to answer.

The line chart illustrates the number of full-time workers in the UK from May 1992 to December 2021, measured in thousands. The data shows fluctuations over the years, with the lowest number recorded at 19,000 in January 1993 and the highest at 24,500 in December 2021. There is an overall trend of increasing numbers of full-time workers over the period, with minor dips and rises throughout the years.

The line chart illustrates the fluctuating exchange rate between the Euro (EUR) and Danish kroner (DKK) over a period from January 2012 to February 24, 2022. The data points show monthly exchange rates with values ranging from 7.43 to 7.47. Each point on the chart represents a specific date and its corresponding exchange rate, indicating the movement of currency values over time.

The histogram illustrates the main reasons why individuals in Japan did not purchase goods in bulk during April 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic. The leading reason was trust that there would be enough supplies, with 53% of respondents citing this concern. A further 29% were concerned about the unavailability of supplies in the supply market. Some 11% believed it was irresponsible to hoard food and essential items, while 12% had enough food at home. Only 4% stated they would buy in bulk if they had space to store the items, and an additional 4% listed other reasons for not purchasing in bulk.

The bar chart illustrates the main reasons why individuals in Japan did not purchase goods in bulk during 2020 due to COVID-19, segmented by age groups. The 16 to 24-year-olds cited 'I trust that there would be enough supplies locally' and 'I have enough time at home' as their top two reasons. Those aged 25 to 34 years emphasized 'I trust that there would be enough supplies locally' and 'I do not want to hoard food and essential items.' The 35 to 44-year-olds listed 'I do not want to hoard food and essential items' and 'I trust that there would be enough supplies locally.' The 45 to 54-year-olds prioritized 'I do not want to hoard food and essential items' and 'I trust that there would be enough supplies locally.' Lastly, the 55 years and older group's main reasons were 'I do not want to hoard food and essential items' and 'I trust that there would be enough supplies locally.'

The bar chart illustrates the sustainable cotton usage scores of various European apparel retailers in 2020. H&M Group leads with a score of 77, followed by C&A at 69, and Marks & Spencer Group plc at 66. Bestseller A/S has a score of 51, while Benetton Group S.r.l. and Esprit Holdings Ltd both score 40. Next plc is at 25, New Look at 19, Associated British Foods plc (Primark) at 16, and MAITEX S.A. has the lowest score of 15.

The bar chart illustrates the percentage reductions in nitrogen dioxide (NO2) emissions for select European cities during COVID-19 lockdowns in 2020 compared to 2019. Paris, France, saw a 45% reduction; Rome, Italy, experienced a 30% decrease; Madrid, Spain, had a 25% reduction; and Milan, Italy, recorded a 20% reduction in NO2 emissions due to the lockdown measures implemented.

The bar chart illustrates student well-being in upper secondary education in Denmark from 2018 to 2020, categorized by type. Individual educational wellbeing scores increased from 3.8 in 2018 to 3.7 in 2020. Social wellbeing improved steadily from 4.1 in 2018 to 4.1 in 2020. The educational environment showed a slight decrease from 3.5 in 2018 to 3.6 in 2020. Pressure and concerns decreased from 2.7 in 2018 to 2.7 in 2020. Lastly, bullying remained constant at 4.9 across all three years.

The histogram illustrates annual salaries in the NBA for 2019-2020, showing three categories: average salaries, median salaries, and total salaries. The average salary is listed at $4.5 million, with the median salary slightly lower at $4.3 million. The total salaries sum up to $3700 million.

The pie chart illustrates the distribution of hospital expenditure across five different services in select countries worldwide for the year 2019. Inpatient care accounts for 45% of the expenditure, while day care and outpatient care each represent 20%. Long-term care constitutes 10%, and other services make up the remaining 15%. The data is segmented by service type to show the proportional allocation of healthcare costs.

The histogram illustrates the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on summer travel plans in Finland for 2020. It shows five categories: "I will not travel at all" with 52%, "I will reduce traveling" with 36%, "I will travel domestically instead of traveling abroad" with 17%, "Other impact" with 6%, and "I do not know" with 2%.

The bar chart illustrates the new production capacity of low-density polyethylene worldwide between 2019 and 2021, measured in thousands of metric tons, by country. The United States leads with a capacity of 820 thousand metric tons, followed by Russia at 400 thousand metric tons, China at 150 thousand metric tons, and South Korea at 150 thousand metric tons as well.

The histogram illustrates the extent of hospital coverage by governments or compulsory insurance schemes in select countries worldwide for 2019. It shows the percentage share of hospital inpatient costs covered, ranging from 48% in Brazil to 99% in Sweden and Norway. Other countries like Estonia, Germany, France, and the Czech Republic also have high coverage rates at 97%, 96%, 95%, and 93%, respectively. The data includes various other nations with varying levels of coverage, such as the United States at 88%, Japan at 91%, and Australia at 64%.

The bar chart illustrates various online activities during the coronavirus pandemic in Poland as of May 2020. It shows that 48% of individuals used online banking, 42% settled health issues online, 41% learned new things, 16% engaged in coding, and 11% learned drawing through online platforms.

The line chart illustrates the length of various tram lines in Paris from 2009 to 2016. Line T1 starts at 5 km in 2009 and increases to 7 km by 2016. Line T2 begins at 8 km, reaching 10 km in 2016. T3a grows from 10 km to 14 km over the years, while T3b remains constant at 10 km. Line T4 is steady at 15 km, T5 fluctuates between 7 and 10 km, T6 rises from 5 to 14 km, and T7 and T8 both increase from 5 to 11 km.

The line chart illustrates the number of vaccine-preventable disease cases worldwide from 1980 to 2019, categorized by disease. The data includes congenital rubella syndrome, diphtheria, measles, mumps, pertussis, polio, rubella, and tetanus. For instance, in 1980, there were 500 cases of measles compared to 300 cases of diphtheria. By 2019, measles cases decreased to 100 while diphtheria cases increased to 400. Each disease shows a distinct trend over the years, with some diseases like measles and rubella showing a significant decrease in cases over time.

The line chart illustrates the market capital value of Europe's largest banks over time, from December 2019 to January 2022. HSBC Holdings (UK) shows fluctuations with values ranging from 85 in February 2020 to 145 in January 2022. BNP Paribas (France) has a range between 35 and 87, while UBS (Switzerland) fluctuates between 30 and 65. Banco Santander (Spain) ranges from 35 to 75, ING Group (Netherlands) from 20 to 60, and Lloyds Banking Group (UK) from 25 to 55. The data points represent monthly changes in their respective market capital values.

The bar chart illustrates the production of various items related to COVID-19 prevention in Poland for two time periods: March to December 2020 and January to June 2021. It shows that protective clothing (overalls, aprons) increased from 15,000 units to 2,000 units, face masks used in medicine rose from 40,000 to 70,000 units, other protective face masks grew from 180,000 to 98,000 units, disposable plastic film gloves went up from 5,000 to 3,000 units, and protective face shields saw an increase from 15,000 to 2,000 units.

The pie chart illustrates the market share of radiation therapy quality assurance phantoms worldwide by region in 2018. North America leads with a 35% share, followed by Europe at 29%, and Asia Pacific at 26%. Latin America accounts for 6%, the Middle East holds 2%, and Africa has the smallest share at 2%.

The line chart illustrates the change in Poland's total population from 1950 to 2020, measured in thousands. The data points show fluctuations over the decades, with an initial increase from 420,000 in 1950 to 530,000 in 1960, followed by a decline and subsequent rises and falls. By 2020, the population decreased to 80,000, indicating a net decrease of 340,000 individuals compared to 1950. The chart captures the population trend with peaks and troughs across the seven-decade period.

The line chart illustrates monthly changes in consumer prices of food products consumed at home during the COVID-19 outbreak in the U.S. in 2021. The data spans from October 2019 to April 2021, showing fluctuations in price growth. In October 2019, there was a 0.2% increase, which decreased to -0.1% by December 2019. Growth peaked in April 2020 with a 2.6% increase, followed by a decline and fluctuation throughout the year, including a notable drop to -0.5% in July 2020. The trend shows a general increase in price growth over time, with April 2021 recording a 0.4% rise.

The histogram illustrates the reasons people in Great Britain left their homes during lockdown in May 2020. The most common reason was shopping for basic necessities, with 80 instances reported. Subsequent reasons included exercising or walking (71), visiting friends or family to provide care or to help them avoid isolation (28), and socializing with people in public spaces (15). Less frequent reasons were going to the doctor or pharmacy (3), meeting with clients or colleagues (2), participating in religious activities (2), and engaging in personal exercise or sport (1). The least common reason was leaving home for other activities, which occurred only once.

The bar chart illustrates the weekly sales growth of fresh foods in the United States during the COVID-19 outbreak in 2020. The data spans from March 8 to April 17, with sales growth percentages for each week. On March 8, sales grew by 5%, and this trend increased steadily, reaching 65% by March 22. Sales growth then decreased slightly to 20% by March 29, before rising again to 24% by April 5. Finally, on April 17, sales growth was at 17%.

The line chart illustrates the Return on Equity (ROE) ratio of Absa Group from 2017 to 2019. In 2017, the ROE was at 14.2%, which decreased to 13.8% in 2018 and further to 13.4% in 2019. The data points for each year show a downward trend in the ROE ratio over the three-year period.

The rose chart illustrates the share of French households with credits over a span from 1989 to 2019. Each year is represented as a segment, with the percentage indicating the proportion of households with credits. The data shows fluctuations over the years, with percentages ranging from 30% in 2016 and 2017 to 34% in 2005 and 2006. The chart captures the trend of credit ownership among French households over three decades.

The bar chart illustrates public opinion on abortion by state in Mexico for 2019, showing the percentage of people who agree and disagree with the practice. The states range from Baja California to Chiapas, with varying opinions. For example, Baja California has 53% agreeing and 45% disagreeing, while Chiapas shows 23% agreement and 75% disagreement. Each state's stance is represented as two bars, one for 'Agree' and another for 'Disagree', indicating the distribution of public opinion across different regions.

The histogram illustrates the total number of foreign tourist arrivals at hotels in various regions of France for 2017, measured in thousands. Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes had 3000 arrivals, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté 1500, Île-de-France 600, Brittany 900, Centre-Val de Loire 900, Corsica 300, Great East 3000, Hauts-de-France 1400, Normandy 1100, Nouvelle Aquitaine 1600, Occitanie 2200, Pays de la Loire 400, and Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur 4000.

The histogram illustrates daily new COVID-19 cases in South Korea from January 20, 2020, to February 11, 2022. The data shows fluctuations over time, with the lowest number of cases recorded on March 15, 2020, at 34 and the highest on February 11, 2022, at 55,678. Cases generally increased over the period, peaking in late 2021 and early 2022 before declining slightly towards the end of the observed timeframe.

The line chart illustrates the monthly Consumer Price Index (CPI) of oils and fats in South Africa from March 2019 to March 2020. The data points show fluctuations over the year, starting at 97 in March 2019 and reaching a peak of 104 in March 2020. There is a general upward trend with some dips, such as a decrease from 101 in September to 98 in July 2019. The CPI fluctuates between 97 and 104 across the months displayed.

The line chart illustrates the total tourist expenditure in museums, shows, and cultural activities in France from 2010 to 2017, measured in billion euros. The data points show a gradual increase over the years, starting at 2.05 billion euros in 2010 and reaching 2.53 billion euros by 2017. There is a slight dip in expenditure in 2011 to 2.00 billion euros before it rises again in subsequent years.

The histogram illustrates the breakdown of average daily tourism spending by visitors from the Middle East to Paris in 2016, categorized by expenditure item. Accommodation costs averaged at $38, while shopping expenses were slightly lower at $22. Food and catering had an average spend of $21. Leisure activities, including shows and museums, cost on average $12, and transport within the region was the least expensive category at $6.

The histogram illustrates public perception of safety outdoors during the COVID-19 outbreak in Great Britain in May 2020. It shows five categories: 'Very safe' with 5% of respondents, 'Safe' with 22%, 'Neither safe nor unsafe' with 27%, 'Unsafe' with 34%, and 'Very unsafe' with 7%. The data reflects the varying levels of perceived safety among individuals when outside their homes due to the pandemic.

The line chart illustrates the monthly Consumer Price Index (CPI) of the footwear industry in South Africa from March 2019 to March 2020. The data points show fluctuations over the year, starting at 103.0 in March 2019 and reaching a peak of 104.5 in March 2020. There is an overall upward trend with minor dips and rises throughout the months, indicating changes in prices or inflation rates within the footwear sector during this period.

The line chart illustrates the monthly Consumer Price Index (CPI) of owner's equivalent rent in South Africa for the period from March 2019 to March 2020. The data points show fluctuations in CPI values, starting at 108.5 in March 2019 and reaching a peak of 112.3 by March 2020. There is a general upward trend in the CPI over the year, with slight variations between months.

The bar chart illustrates the popularity of video games among girls aged 9-10 years in Norway during 2020. Roblox leads with a value of 65, followed by Minecraft at 42. Fortnite is played by 7% of the group, while FIFA and Gacha Life have lower values of 4 and 3 respectively.

The bar chart illustrates the popularity of video games among boys aged 9-10 years in Norway during 2020. Fortnite leads with a value of 55, followed by Minecraft at 38, Roblox at 37, FIFA at 23, and Pokémon at 6. The data suggests a descending order of preference for these games within the specified age group.

The histogram illustrates the total contribution of travel and tourism to the gross domestic product (GDP) in Latin American countries for 2020, measured in billion U.S. dollars. Mexico leads with $93.5 billion, followed by Brazil at $77.8 billion, and Argentina at $25.1 billion. Chile contributes $16.4 billion, Peru $9.5 billion, and Colombia $6.8 billion. Other countries like Cuba, the Dominican Republic, Uruguay, Panama, Costa Rica, Guatemala, Ecuador, Venezuela, Honduras, El Salvador, Bolivia, Paraguay, and Nicaragua contribute progressively smaller amounts, ranging from $0.1 billion to $2.5 billion.

The bar chart illustrates public opinion on abortion in Brazil for 2021, segmented by income level. It shows two categories: those in favor and against abortion. Individuals without a fixed income have 28% in favor and 63% against. Those earning up to 2 minimum wages show 38% in favor and 49% against. The 2 to 5 minimum wages group has 27% in favor and 69% against. For those earning 5 to 10 minimum wages, opinions split evenly at 37% each. Lastly, individuals with an income over 10 minimum wages have 36% in favor and 42% against.

The line chart illustrates the consumption of antibiotics by city-dwellers in France from 2000 to 2016, measured in defined daily doses per 1,000 inhabitants and per day. The data shows fluctuations over the years, starting at 32.5 in 2000 and ending at 31.8 in 2016. There is a general downward trend until 2004, followed by an increase and subsequent peaks and troughs, with the lowest consumption recorded in 2004 at 27.2 and the highest in 2000 at 32.5.

The pie chart illustrates China's share in U.S. imports of various antibiotic products in 2019. Chloramphenicol and derivatives lead with a 28% share, followed by tetracyclines and derivatives at 26%. Penicillin and derivatives account for 15%, while antibiotics total comprises 11%. Streptomycins and derivatives make up 9%, erythromycin and derivatives represent 7%, and other antibiotics (NESOI) constitute 7% of the market share.

The bar chart illustrates changes in consumer spending on grocery delivery due to the coronavirus, segmented by income brackets. Individuals earning under $50K report 20% more spending, 55% no change, 9% less spending, and 16% unsure or without an opinion. Those with incomes between $50K-100K show 26% more spending, 58% no change, 8% less spending, and 10% unsure. Lastly, those with an income of $100K+ indicate 29% more spending, 54% no change, 7% less spending, and 9% unsure.

The bar chart illustrates the average carrier billing transaction value in Guatemala for each month from April 2019 to April 2020, measured in U.S. dollars. The data shows fluctuations with values ranging from $2.00 in August and September 2019 to $2.15 in April 2019 and February 2020. There is no indication of the specific number of transactions or the total revenue generated by these transactions.

The bar chart illustrates the average revenue per paying user (ARPPU) with carrier billing in Guatemala for each month from April 2019 to April 2020. The ARPPU values fluctuate, starting at $2.1 in April 2019 and reaching its peak of $4.1 in September 2019. There is a general upward trend until October 2019, followed by a slight decrease to $2.5 in November and December 2019. The subsequent months show an increase, peaking again at $3.4 in February 2020 before dropping to $2.0 in March and April 2020.

The histogram illustrates the breakdown of hotel rooms by arrondissement in Paris for the year 2017. The data shows that the 8th and 9th arrondissements have the highest number of hotel rooms, both with 10.5 rooms. The 1st arrondissement follows with 5.1 rooms, while the 17th has 9.3 rooms. The 4th arrondissement has the fewest with 1.1 rooms. Other arrondissements range from 1.6 to 8.2 rooms, with no two consecutive arrondissements having the same number of rooms.

The pie chart illustrates the distribution of expenses for raising two children in a 2+2 family in Poland during 2020. Food accounts for 30% of the costs, followed by apartment expenses at 24%. Transport and communications make up 16%, while education costs represent 10%. Culture and recreation take up 6%, clothing and footwear 5%, other expenses 3%, health care 3%, and personal hygiene also constitutes 3% of the total expenses.

The bar chart illustrates the median carrier billing transaction value in Uruguay for each month from April 2019 to April 2020, measured in U.S. dollars. The data shows fluctuations over the period, with values ranging from $0.60 in March and April 2020 to $0.80 in April 2019. Each month's median transaction value is represented as a separate bar, indicating a monthly snapshot of the billing activity within the carrier sector.

The pie chart illustrates the distribution of responses to the question about plans for having children in Poland in 2020. It shows that 26% of respondents plan to definitely have children, while 23% prefer rather yes. Those who find it hard to say make up 16%, and 14% prefer rather not. Lastly, 21% of respondents definitely do not plan to have children.

The histogram illustrates the distribution of COVID-19 cases in the United States as of March 6, 2022, by ethnicity. The data shows that White Non-Hispanic individuals had the highest number of cases at 54.3%, followed by Hispanic/Latino at 24.7%. Black Non-Hispanics accounted for 12.5% of the cases, while Multiple/Other Non-Hispanics represented 4.3%. Asian Non-Hispanics had 3.8%, American Indian/Alaska Native Non-Hispanics 1.2%, and Pacific Islander Non-Hispanics had the fewest cases at 0.4%.

The bar chart illustrates changes in radio listening habits during the COVID-19 outbreak in Hungary in 2020. It shows three categories: "I listen to the radio more," with 33 individuals, "I listen to the radio less," with 12 individuals, and "I listen to the radio the same amount of time," with 56 individuals. The data reflects how people's radio listening habits have altered since the onset of the pandemic.

The bar chart illustrates the global distribution of polypropylene production by application in 2017. Packaging leads with 49% of the production, followed by consumer and institutional products at 22%. Transportation - other accounts for 15%, while building and construction represent 7%. Electrical/electronic applications make up 5%, industrial/machinery 1%, and personal care products have the smallest share at 0.3%.

The bar chart illustrates the responses to various precautionary measures against the coronavirus in Hungary during 2020. It shows the percentage of people who answered 'Yes' or 'No' to questions about washing hands, hand disinfection, wearing a medical mask, avoiding crowded places, and avoiding Chinese buffets, restaurants, and shops. For example, 32% said they washed their hands, while 68% did not. Hand disinfection was practiced by 59%, with 41% not doing so. The use of masks was low at 2%, with 98% not wearing them. Avoiding crowded places was done by 32%, and 68% did not. Lastly, 12% avoided Chinese establishments, with 88% not doing so.

The bar chart illustrates changes in radio listening habits during COVID-19 in Hungary, 2020, categorized by program type. It shows three groups: those who listen more, less, or the same amount of time as before. For news, information, and weather programs, 38% listen more, 11% listen less, and 51% listen the same. Music programs see 26% increased listenership, 11% decreased, and 63% unchanged. Morning shows have 23% more listeners, 20% fewer, and 57% maintaining the same listening habits.

The histogram illustrates the number of coronavirus (COVID-19) deaths in the U.S. as of March 2, 2021, categorized by race. The data shows that whites account for 300,000 deaths, Latinos for 90,000, blacks for 70,000, and Asians for 18,000. Smaller numbers are observed among the 'Other' group with 10,000 deaths, indigenous populations at 5,000, and Pacific Islanders with just 1,000 deaths.

The bar chart illustrates the top reasons for eating more home-cooked meals in Hungary during the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020. The most important reason was having more time for cooking, followed by cooking being cheaper at home, and working from home enabling this change. Other reasons included the ability to control ingredients, better quality of food, and the convenience of not having to go out.

The bar chart illustrates the percentage of COVID-19 deaths among Indigenous populations compared to their respective state populations in the United States as of June 23, 2020. New Mexico shows a higher percentage of COVID-19 deaths at 60% compared to its population percentage of 8%. Arizona follows with 20% deaths and a 4% population percentage. Mississippi has 6% deaths against a 0.5% population percentage. Other states like Minnesota, Wisconsin, Washington, California, North Carolina, Michigan, and Oklahoma have lower percentages of both deaths and population representation. The data suggests a disparity between the percentage of deaths and the overall population percentage for each state.

The bar chart illustrates the share of youth in Sweden who play online games daily and overall by age group in 2019. For those aged 11 to 13, 72% play daily, with an 85% total share. The 14 to 16-year-olds have a 64% daily player ratio and an 88% total share. Lastly, 38% of 17 to 19-year-olds play daily, representing an 89% total share among this age group.

The bar chart illustrates the breakdown of conference centers' turnover in France in 2017, categorized by business sector. Royalties and other income account for 10% of the turnover, event planning for 5%, trade fair reception also at 10%, and the largest share with 75% comes from the reception of congresses, corporate events, and cultural events.

The histogram illustrates public support for protests in response to George Floyd's death, categorized by age groups in the U.S. 2020. The '18 to 34' group shows 50% strongly supporting and 23% somewhat supporting the protests. The '35 to 44' group has 42% strong support and 27% somewhat support. For those aged '45 to 64', there is 35% strong support and 26% somewhat support. The '65 and older' group has 28% strong support and 27% somewhat support. The 'Strongly oppose' category increases with age, from 12% to 20%.

The histogram illustrates the U.S. adults' views on companies supporting protesters in demonstrations over George Floyd's death in U.S. cities as of June 2020. It shows four categories: 'More favorable view' at 25%, 'Less favorable view' at 30%, 'No impact either way' at 27%, and 'Don't know / no opinion' at 18%.

The histogram illustrates the number of foreigners in Poland by nationality in 2019. Ukraine leads with 1,350,000 individuals, followed by Belarus at 100,000 and Germany at 75,000. Moldova has 40,000, Russia 35,000, India 30,000, Georgia 25,000, Vietnam 20,000, Turkey 15,000, and China 10,000. The 'Others' category accounts for 350,000 foreigners.

The bar chart illustrates the supply status of various COVID-19 Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) items in healthcare facilities in the U.S. for April 2020. It categorizes each item by the duration of supply remaining: no supply, one week or less, two weeks or less, and more than two weeks. For instance, N95 masks show 20% with no supply remaining, 40% lasting one week or less, 28% lasting two weeks or less, and 12% lasting more than two weeks. Surgical masks, face shields, booties, gloves, gowns, hand sanitizer, disinfecting wipes, and thermometers also have varying percentages across these categories.

The bar chart illustrates Hungarians' perception of online news portals regarding the coronavirus (COVID-19) in 2020. It shows three categories: 71% believe some online news portals cause unnecessary panic through their reporting, 25% think they just provide information without causing panic, and 4% either do not know or refuse to answer the question.

The bar chart illustrates public support for the police during the George Floyd protests, segmented by ethnicity in the U.S. 2020. It shows six categories of response: strongly support, somewhat support, neither support nor oppose, somewhat oppose, strongly oppose, and don't know/no opinion. Whites show 31% strongly supporting, Hispanics 16%, African-Americans 4%, and others 20%. Whites have the highest 'neither support nor oppose' at 18%, while African-Americans lead with 20% strongly opposing. The 'don't know/no opinion' category is highest among African-Americans and 'Other' groups at 6%.

The line chart illustrates Dell Technologies' revenue from 2015 to 2021, segmented by different product lines and groups. It shows yearly revenues in billions for Servers and Networking (Infrastructure Solutions Group), Storage (Infrastructure Solutions Group), Commercial (Client Solutions Group), Consumer (Client Solutions Group), and VMware. By 2021, Servers and Networking increased to $11.5 billion, Storage to $10.5 billion, Commercial to $14.5 billion, Consumer to $11.5 billion, and VMware to $10.5 billion.

The pie chart illustrates the distribution of COVID-19 cases in Canada as of April 2020, categorized by their travel-related status. It shows that 26% of the cases were travel-related, while the remaining 74% fall into other categories.

The bar chart illustrates the frequency of remote work before and after the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States in 2020. It shows that before the pandemic, 48 individuals never worked remotely, while 34 did so less than once per week. After the pandemic, there were 34 individuals who never worked remotely, 8 who worked less than once per week, 6 working 1-2 days per week, 9 working 3-4 days per week, and 45 working 5 or more days per week.

The histogram illustrates the breakdown of Singapore's nominal GDP by sector in 2020. Transportation and storage contribute 6.0%, while Administrative and support services make up 4.7%. Real estate accounts for 3.8%, Construction for 2.7%, Retail trade for 1.5%, Utilities and beverages for 1.4%, and Accommodation for 0.6%.

The line chart illustrates the number of unique podcast downloads delivered by LibSyn worldwide in 2018 and 2019, measured in billions. In 2018, there were 5.1 billion downloads, which increased to 6.2 billion in 2019. The data points for each year show a consistent upward trend in podcast downloads over the given period.

The histogram illustrates the rate of fatal police shootings in the United States from 2015 to March 2022, categorized by ethnicity. The data shows that for every million people, there were 38 fatal police shootings among Black individuals, 28 among Hispanics, 15 among Whites, and 5 among those classified as Other.

The line chart illustrates the monthly Consumer Price Index (CPI) of recreational equipment in South Africa over a period from March 2019 to March 2020. There is a general downward trend after May, with the CPI dropping to its lowest point of 95.0 in March 2020. The histogram illustrates public opinion on the positive effects of COVID-19 in Hungary as of April 2020. It shows that 45 people believe the pandemic has led to cleaner, healthier cities, while 37 think families spend more time together. The number decreases with 33 people agreeing that it has helped manage work and school from home. Fewer respondents, 30, see it as an opportunity for personal growth, and 29 believe it has reduced traffic congestion. The least positive effect is perceived by 22 people who think it has decreased spending on non-essential items.

The histogram illustrates the number of deals made by leading venture investors in privacy and security companies during 2019. The bar chart illustrates the growth of COVID-19-related content on the Internet in Poland during various weeks in 2020, measured by average posts per hour and minute. In Week 10 (02-16.02), there were 200 average posts per hour and 3 average posts per minute. The following week saw an increase to 250 posts/hour and 4 posts/minute. The trend continued with Week 24 (02-01.03) at 1700 posts/hour and 20 posts/minute, and Week 02 (03-08.03) at 1900 posts/hour and 25 posts/minute. The peak was observed in Week 09 (03-15.03) with 5200 posts/hour and 60 posts/minute, followed by Week 16 (03-22.03) with 5100 posts/hour and 65 posts/minute.

The bar chart illustrates the harvested area of bananas in Angola for two consecutive crop years, 2017/18 and 2018/19. In the 2017/18 crop year, the harvested area was recorded at 140,000 hectares, whereas it increased to 145,000 hectares in the 2018/19 crop year.

The bar chart illustrates the popularity of various entertainment platforms among kids and teens, as perceived by U.S. parents in 2020, segmented by age group. YouTube leads with 62% preference across all ages, followed by Netflix at 55%, Disney+ at 41%, and YouTube Kids at 23%. Other platforms like Instagram, TikTok, Minecraft, Fortnite, PBS Kids, Cartoon Network, Roblox, Twitter, Amazon FreeTime, and Noggin show varying levels of interest among parents of children under age 5, ages 5-12, and ages 13-17. For instance, while YouTube Kids is preferred by 23% overall, it peaks at 48% for parents of children ages 5-12.

The pie chart illustrates the distribution of responses to whether Poles touched shop products less often during the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020. A majority, 66.3%, answered 'Yes', indicating they touched products less frequently. A smaller portion, 28.9%, responded 'No', suggesting they continued to touch products as usual. Lastly, 4.8% chose 'I don't know', reflecting uncertainty or lack of information on this matter.

The bar chart illustrates the output value of forestry and connected secondary activities in Denmark from 2012 to 2017, measured in million euros. In 2012, the output was 635 million euros, which increased to 680 million euros by 2013. The following year saw a slight decrease to 675 million euros. Output values fluctuated in subsequent years, reaching 655 million euros in 2015, dipping to 605 million euros in 2016, and then rising to 650 million euros in 2017.

The bar chart illustrates the gross value of oranges in South Africa from 2000 to 2019, measured in thousands of South African rands. The data shows fluctuations over the years, starting at 10,000 rand in 2000 and reaching its peak at 11,000 rand in 2019. There is an overall upward trend with some variations, such as a dip in 2005 to 15,000 rand and a slight decrease in 2006 to 18,000 rand. The values generally increase each year, with the exception of a minor decline in 2007 to 30,000 rand.

The bar chart illustrates the number of tourists in accommodation establishments in Poland during the COVID-19 epidemic between 2019 and 2020, measured in thousands. In Q1 '19, there were 6700 thousand tourists, which increased to 9400 thousand in Q2 '19. The peak occurred in Q3 '19 with 11800 thousand tourists. There was a decline in Q4 '19 to 7900 thousand. The year 2020 saw a significant drop in Q2 '20 with 1800 thousand tourists, followed by an increase to 8100 thousand in Q3 '20 and a further decrease to 2500 thousand in Q4 '20.

The line chart illustrates the output value of forestry and connected secondary activities in Latvia from 2009 to 2017, measured in million euros. The data shows fluctuations over the years, starting at 1050 million euros in 2009, peaking at 1600 million euros in 2011, and then declining to 850 million euros in 2012. Subsequent years show varying values, with a high of 1600 million euros again in 2017. The chart captures the economic trend of these activities over this period.

The histogram illustrates the anxiety levels across different regions of the UK in 2021, using an average score on a scale from 0 to 10. Wales has the highest anxiety level at 3.4, followed by London and Yorkshire & Humberside both at 3.4. The West Midlands, North West, and North East regions have scores of 3.3 each. Scotland's anxiety level is slightly lower at 3.2, while the East Midlands, South East, and South West regions all have scores of 3.1. East England has the lowest anxiety level depicted at 3.2, and Northern Ireland has the lowest overall score of 3.1.

The bar chart illustrates the number of employed people in Denmark during Q1 2020 and Q1 2021, categorized by industry. Public administration, education, and health saw an increase from 895,000 to 930,000 employees. Manufacturing and mining experienced a rise from 705,000 to 675,000. The category of 'Other industries and quarrying' went up from 330,000 to 340,000. Services employment decreased slightly from 315,000 to 305,000. Construction had 165,000 employees in Q1 2020 compared to 180,000 in 2021. Information sector employment grew from 105,000 to 110,000. Arts, entertainment, and recreation increased from 100,000 to 105,000. Financial and insurance sectors had 95,000 employees in both years. Agriculture, forestry, and fishing saw a decrease from 55,000 to 50,000. Real estate employment was at 50,000 in both quarters. Lastly, activity not stated remained constant at 30,000.

The bar chart illustrates the number of employed people in Denmark during Q3 2020 and Q3 2021, categorized by sector. Private corporations lead with 1,800,000 employees in 2020 and 1,900,000 in 2021. Municipal government employment stands at 500,000 in both years. Central government shows an increase from 200,000 to 250,000. Regional government has 150,000 employees in 2020 and 170,000 in 2021. Private nonprofit organizations have 100,000 employees, while public corporations have 60,000. Social security funds employ 10,000 individuals, and the sector not stated accounts for 50,000 employees in 2020 and 60,000 in 2021.

The line chart illustrates Guatemala's chicken meat production volume from 2010 to 2019, measured in thousands of metric tons. The data shows an overall increase in production over the years, starting at 175 thousand metric tons in 2010 and reaching 260 thousand metric tons by 2019. There is a slight dip in 2012 with 190 thousand metric tons, but the trend generally rises each year, with notable increases in 2014 and 2018. The chart includes projections for 2019, indicating a continued upward trajectory.

The bar chart illustrates the percentage of U.S. consumers avoiding shopping centers/malls and shops in general, categorized by age groups during the coronavirus outbreak. The 18-29 age group shows 68% avoiding shopping centers/malls and 45% avoiding shops in general. For those aged 30-44, the percentages are 67% for shopping centers/malls and 56% for shops in general. The 45-60 age bracket reports 79% avoiding shopping centers/malls and 54% avoiding shops in general. Lastly, the 61+ age group has 85% avoiding shopping centers/malls and 61% avoiding shops in general.

The line chart illustrates the output value of forestry and connected secondary activities in Norway from 2009 to 2017, measured in billion euros. The data shows fluctuations over the years, starting at 0.83 billion euros in 2009 and reaching a peak of 1.25 billion euros in both 2011 and 2017. There is a dip in 2012 with a value of 1.15 billion euros, followed by a gradual increase to 1.17 billion euros in 2014 before another decline to 1.06 billion euros in 2016.

The histogram illustrates the number of followers in millions for the top U.S. TikTok influencers as of July 2020. The bar chart illustrates the gross value added by the forestry and logging industry in Estonia from 2012 to 2017, measured in million euros. The upward trend continued with values reaching 260.4 million euros in 2014, 275.9 million euros in 2015, and 268.3 million euros in 2016. However, there was a slight decrease in 2017 to 249.7 million euros.

The line chart illustrates the gross value added by the forestry and logging industry in Germany from 2009 to 2017, measured in billion euros. The data shows an initial increase from 1.8 billion euros in 2009 to 3.6 billion euros in 2012. A slight dip occurs in 2014 with 3.1 billion euros, followed by a rise to 3.7 billion euros in 2016. The trend then decreases to 3.4 billion euros in 2017. Each year is marked on the x-axis, while the corresponding gross value added is plotted on the y-axis.

The line chart illustrates the gross value added by the forestry and logging industry in Croatia from 2012 to 2017, measured in million euros. In 2012, the gross value was 210 million euros, which decreased to 189 million euros in 2013. The following year saw a further decline to 183 million euros. There was a slight increase in 2015 to 184 million euros, but it dropped again in 2016 to 165 million euros before rising to 196 million euros in 2017.

The histogram illustrates the number of Albertsons stores across various states in the United States for 2020. California leads with 593 stores, followed by Washington with 217 and Texas with 184. Arizona has 136 stores, while Oregon features 123. Other states like Colorado, Nevada, New York, and Virginia have between 35 to 80 stores each. The least number of stores is observed in states such as Wyoming, North Dakota, South Dakota, and Vermont, which have only one store each.

The histogram presents opinions on media coverage of the COVID-19 pandemic in Spain for 2020. It shows six categories: 'They have explained how I can cope with the pandemic', 'They have helped me understand the pandemic', 'They have shown too exaggerated a picture about the pandemic', and their corresponding responses ranging from 'Completely disagree' to 'Do not know'. For instance, 6% completely disagreed that the media explained coping methods, while 40% slightly agreed they helped understand the pandemic. The 'Do not know' category is represented by 2% for the first statement and 4% for the third.

The histogram illustrates the popularity of various sports among Russians in terms of their interest in streaming them after lockdown 2020. The data shows that the FIFA World Cup and UEFA European Championship were the most desired streams, with 45 and 31 requests respectively. Other popular choices included the Premier League, NBA, NHL, and the English Football League, with requests ranging from 25 to 17. Less preferred options like the Spanish La Liga, German Bundesliga, and Russian Premier League had fewer requests, between 12 and 9.

The line chart illustrates the number of metal ore mining enterprises in Hungary from 2009 to 2018. In 2009, there were 8 enterprises, which increased to 9 in 2010 and then dropped to 7 in 2011. The following year saw an increase to 10 enterprises, before decreasing to 9 in 2013. A slight decrease occurred in 2014 with 7 enterprises, followed by a rise to 6 in 2015 and 2016. The trend continued downward in 2017 with 4 enterprises and further decreased to 3 in 2018.

The line chart illustrates the number of metal ore mining enterprises in Poland from 2009 to 2018. In 2009, there were 7 enterprises, which increased to 9 by 2010 and then to 12 in 2011. The following year saw a slight decrease to 11 enterprises. The number rose again in 2013 to 12 enterprises before peaking at 18 in 2014. There was a subsequent decline to 15 enterprises in 2015, followed by a further drop to 14 in 2016. The trend continued downward with 12 enterprises in 2017 and an estimated 11 enterprises in 2018.

The histogram illustrates various measures taken by Russian consumers in response to the COVID-19 outbreak in March 2020. It shows that 32% stopped visiting public events, 22% cancelled trips abroad, and 22% limited their use of public transport. Additionally, 18% stocked personal hygiene products, 7% stocked medicines, and 5% stocked food.

The line chart illustrates the impact of COVID-19 on the HICP forecast by scenario in Spain from 2020 to 2022. It shows three different scenarios: 'Early recovery', 'Gradual recovery', and 'Risky scenario'. In 2020, the 'Early recovery' scenario starts at -0.3, 'Gradual recovery' at -0.5, and 'Risky scenario' at -0.4. By 2022, 'Early recovery' increases to 1.6, 'Gradual recovery' to 1.5, and 'Risky scenario' to 1.2. Each year, all scenarios show an upward trend in their respective values.

The histogram illustrates French expectations of campsite features in 2018. It shows that a good price-performance ratio is the most desired feature at 67%, followed by comfort at 43%. Quality service and safety for children are also highly valued, with 39% and 25% respectively. Diversified catering options and varied sports facilities are expected by 20% and 16% of respondents. Entertainment availability at any time of the day is anticipated by 15%, while wellness services like massages and spas are expected by 13%. Lastly, other unspecified features are desired by 7%, and an option not pronounced is chosen by 4%.

The histogram illustrates the Gross Domestic Product per capita (in GBP) across different regions of the UK in 2019. London leads with a GDP per capita of £57,436, followed by the South East at £35,890 and the United Kingdom as a whole at £33,250. The East of England has a GDP per capita of £30,670, while Scotland stands at £30,450. The South West, North West, and West Midlands have lower figures ranging from £28,960 to £27,430. The East Midlands, Yorkshire and the Humber, Northern Ireland, Wales, and the North East show decreasing GDP per capita values, ending with the North East at £24,120.

The ring chart illustrates the share of arts, entertainment, and recreation businesses trading in the UK over various weeks from 2020 to 2021. Each slice represents a week's worth of data, with percentages indicating the trading activity. For example, the week of August 9-22, 2021, shows a 4.4% share, while the week of June 15-28, 2020, has a smaller share at 1.2%. The data spans from early 2020 through mid-2021, capturing fluctuations in business trading across different weeks.

The bar chart illustrates the comparable store sales growth percentages for Walmart and Sam's Club in the United States during 2021. Walmart U.S. reported a 9% increase, while Sam's Club saw an 8% rise in its comparable store sales. The total U.S. comparable store sales growth is also presented at 9%.

The line chart illustrates the membership fee revenue of Sam's Club (Walmart) worldwide from 2018 to 2021, measured in billion U.S. dollars. In 2018, the revenue was $1.4 billion, which slightly decreased to $1.4 billion in 2019 and then rose to $1.5 billion in 2020. The upward trend continued in 2021 with a revenue of $1.7 billion.

The bar chart illustrates the importance of different aspects in life in Japan for the year 2019. Family is rated as the most important aspect with a value of 98, followed by friends at 90, leisure time at 90, and work at 80. The chart visually represents these values to show the relative significance of each category.

The bar chart illustrates the number of pupils in primary, general secondary, and vocational schools in Poland over four academic years: 1990/91, 2018/19, 2019/20, and 2020/21. In 1990/91, there were 5340 primary school pupils, 450 general secondary school pupils, and 600 vocational school pupils. By 2018/19, these numbers had decreased to 3050 for primary, 430 for general secondary, and 500 for vocational. The following year saw an increase across all categories with 3070 primary, 580 general secondary, and 650 vocational pupils. In 2020/21, the numbers rose again to 3100 primary, 590 general secondary, and 660 vocational pupils.

The pie chart illustrates the quarterly share of music listeners in Denmark from 2018 to 2021. Each quarter is represented as a slice, with varying percentages indicating the listener share for that period. The data shows consistent shares ranging from 75% to 85%, with slight fluctuations across the years. For instance, Q1 2019 has an 84% share, while Q3 2020 and Q4 2020 both have the highest share at 85%. The chart captures the trend over four years, highlighting the changes in listener share throughout each quarter.

The histogram illustrates the number of residents in certified nursing facilities across various states in the United States as of 2019. California leads with 100,000 residents, followed by Texas and New York with 90,000 and 72,000 respectively. Other states like Florida, Ohio, and Pennsylvania have populations ranging from 65,000 to 35,000 residents in nursing homes. The number decreases progressively with states such as Michigan, Georgia, and Virginia having between 20,000 to 30,000 residents. Smaller states like North Dakota, Vermont, and Alaska have significantly fewer residents, with numbers dropping down to just 2,000 or less.

The bar chart illustrates the level of fear among different age groups in India regarding contracting COVID-19 in 2020, categorized by their responses to being "Very scared," "Fairly scared," "Not very scared," and "Not at all scared." Generation Z shows 26% very scared, 26% fairly scared, 27% not very scared, and 11% not at all scared. Millennials report higher percentages for being very scared (29%) and fairly scared (31%), with lower percentages for the other categories. Generation X indicates 19% very scared, 29% fairly scared, 27% not very scared, and 18% not at all scared. Baby boomers have the highest percentage of those not at all scared (21%), with 11% very scared, 27% fairly scared, and 31% not very scared.

The line chart illustrates the quarterly unemployment rates in Norway from 2018 to 2021, distinguishing between males and females. In Q1 2018, the male unemployment rate was 4.4% compared to 3.5% for females. The trend fluctuates over the years, with peaks such as Q3 2020 at 5.6% for males and 5.2% for females, and troughs like Q2 2019 at 3.8% for males and 3.1% for females. The data shows a general increase in unemployment rates for both genders over the period, with males consistently having slightly higher rates than females.

The line chart illustrates the trend of average actual weekly working hours in Norway from 2010 to 2020. The data shows fluctuations over the years, with an initial increase from 34.1 hours in 2010 to 34.3 hours in 2011 and 2012. A slight decrease is observed in 2013 at 34.0 hours. The following year sees a rise back to 34.3 hours, then a dip to 33.9 hours in 2015. The trend continues with a fluctuation between 33.9 and 34.1 hours until 2018, after which there's a noticeable decline, ending at 33.6 hours in 2020.

The line chart illustrates the average actual weekly working hours for men and women in Norway from 2010 to 2020. In 2010, men worked an average of 37.5 hours per week compared to women's 27.5 hours. Over the years, there is a fluctuating trend with men's hours generally decreasing from 38.0 hours in 2011 to 35.5 hours in 2020. Women's hours show a slight increase from 27.5 hours in 2010 to 30.5 hours in 2017 before slightly decreasing to 29.5 hours by 2020.

The bar chart illustrates the average monthly salary in Norway for 2020, broken down by gender across three sectors: private sector and public enterprises, local government, and central government. Men earn an average of $52,000 compared to women's $45,000 in the private sector and public enterprises. In local government, men have an average salary of $46,000 versus women's $43,000. The central government shows men earning $58,000 on average against women's $50,000.

The line chart illustrates the planted area of sugar cane in Kenya from 2015 to 2020, measured in thousands of hectares. In 2015, the area was at 230 thousand hectares, which decreased to 220 thousand in 2016. There was a further decline to 192 thousand hectares in 2017 before an increase to 224 thousand hectares in 2018. The following year saw a slight decrease to 198 thousand hectares, and projections for 2020 suggest an increase to 204 thousand hectares.

The bar chart illustrates the global mental health of workers before and after the COVID-19 outbreak in April 2020. Before the pandemic, 45% of workers were perfectly healthy with no challenges, while 7% faced non-functional or extremely challenging situations. In the past week, the percentages shifted to 32% perfectly healthy without challenges and 15% experiencing non-functional or extremely challenging conditions.

The histogram illustrates the opinions of Hungarians on the necessity of conducting regular PCR tests at their workplaces to detect COVID-19 cases in 2020. A majority, 57%, believe it is important to conduct such tests regularly. Conversely, 19% think it is not necessary, while 16% do not work and thus have no opinion. Additionally, 5% consider it unnecessary due to the nature of their job, and 3% are unsure or did not provide an answer.

The pie chart illustrates the distribution of workers' stress levels since the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020. It shows that 67% of workers experienced an increase in stress, 25% reported their stress levels as somewhat equal, and 8% noted a decrease in stress levels.

The line chart illustrates the production volume of sugar in Kenya from 2016 to 2020, measured in thousands of metric tons. In 2016, the production was at 640 thousand metric tons, which decreased to 320 thousand metric tons in 2017. There was an increase in 2018 with 490 thousand metric tons, followed by a slight decrease to 440 thousand metric tons in 2019. The production rose again in 2020 to 610 thousand metric tons.

The bar chart illustrates the preferences of Belarusians regarding their dependency on government services across five areas: welfare, health, education, education of children, and employment in 2019. Respondents were asked to indicate whether they depend on themselves, the state, both, or did not provide an answer. Welfare shows 58% depending on themselves, while health has the highest 'depends on myself' at 74%. Education and employment have similar percentages for 'depends on myself', with 52% and 49%, respectively. Health also leads in those who depend on the state (6%). The area of education of children has the highest percentage of those depending on both (30%).

The bar chart illustrates the hotel market segmentation brand signings in India from 2018 to 2020, categorized by number of keys. Commercial destinations saw an increase from 58 keys in 2018 to 63 keys in 2020. Leisure destinations started at 33 keys in 2018 and rose to 41 keys in 2020. Mixed destinations had the lowest numbers, with 9 keys in 2018, increasing to 10 keys in 2020.

The histogram illustrates the direct contribution of the travel and tourism sector to total employment in Africa for 2019, measured as a percentage by country. The data includes various African nations such as Nigeria, Kenya, and Egypt, with percentages between 1.2% and 2.5%. The chart provides a visual comparison of how different countries contribute to the sector's employment within Africa.

The line chart illustrates the export volume of maize in Kenya from 2016 to 2020, measured in metric tons. In 2016, the export volume was 3200 metric tons, which increased to 5400 metric tons in 2017. There was a decrease in 2018 with 2700 metric tons exported. The line chart illustrates daily new coronavirus (COVID-19) cases in Ethiopia over a period from January 2021 to September 30, 2021. The data points show fluctuations in the number of cases each day, with values ranging from a low of 1 on February 1st to a high of 2458 on August 17th. The histogram illustrates the acceptance of mandatory COVID-19 testing at the workplace in Hungary for 2020, categorized by response levels. The line chart illustrates the share of the travel and tourism sector in employment in Africa from 2008 to 2020. In 2008, this sector accounted for 7.8% of employment. The line chart illustrates the direct contribution of the travel and tourism industry to employment in Ghana from 2008 to 2019. Other years display varying figures, such as 2.2 million jobs in 2008, 1.8 million in 2010, and 1.75 million in 2019. The trend appears to be somewhat erratic without a clear upward or downward trajectory.

The line chart illustrates voting intentions in a Scottish independence referendum from January 2018 to November 2021. By August 2020, 'Yes' votes peaked at 55%, while 'No' votes decreased to 47%. The trend fluctuates, with 'Yes' votes dropping to 47% by November 2021, and 'No' votes rising to 55%.

The line chart illustrates the trend in the number of full-time employees at record labels in Denmark over three periods from 2016 to 2019. In the first half of 2016, there were 195 employees, which increased to 240 by the first half of 2018. The histogram illustrates the reasons why Hungarians did not want to get vaccinated against COVID-19 in 2020. The most common reason was concern about side effects, with 59 individuals citing it. A smaller number, 35, did not believe the vaccine would be effective. Those who felt they were not at enough risk from COVID-19 numbered 22. Another unspecified reason accounted for 15 cases, and the least common reason was a lack of time, with only 1 individual mentioning it.

The bar chart illustrates the price index for rail freight transport in France over a span from Q3 2013 to Q1 2020. Each subsequent quarter shows fluctuations in the index, with peaks such as Q3 2018 at 114 and troughs like Q2 2016 at 97. The chart captures the trend of changes in the price index over these years.

The histogram illustrates the perceived disadvantages of remote and hybrid work models in Poland for 2021. It shows that difficulty in separating work and private life is the most important disadvantage, followed by additional expenses like electricity costs. Less direct contact with colleagues ranks third, while mixing work with home space is considered the fourth concern. The least significant disadvantages include less effectiveness in performance and the company's lack of optimization of remote work practices.

The bar chart illustrates holiday travel expenditure in major regions of Russia during summer 2020, measured in billion Russian rubles. Moscow leads with an expenditure of 9.5 billion rubles, followed by St.Petersburg at 1.7 billion rubles, and Krasnodar Krai with the lowest expenditure of 1.3 billion rubles.

The pie chart illustrates the government net borrowing as a percentage of GDP in Japan from 2012 to 2021. In 2012, the net borrowing was 18.3%, which decreased to 4.5% by 2021.
